aders and Ojibwe hunters. Cree women and their metis daughters. Explorers and anthropologists and Aboriginal guides and informants. These people, their relationships, and their complex identities were not featured in histories until the 1970s, when scholars from multiple disciplines brought new perspectives and approaches to bear on the past. Gathering Places presents some of the most innovative and interdisciplinary approaches to metis, fur trade, and First Nations history being practised today. Whether they are discussing dietary practices on the Plateau, the meanings of totemic signatures, or issues of representation in public history, the authors present novel explorations of evidence that extend beyond earlier histories centred on the archive. By drawing on archaeological, material, oral, and ethnographic evidence and by exploring personal approaches to history and scholarship, these essays mark a significant departure from the old paradigm of history writing and will serve as models for recovering Aboriginal and cross-cultural experiences and perspectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFur tradezCanadaxHistory. 0aIndigenous peoplesxMaterial culturezCanada. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxEthnic identity. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxHistory. 0aMétisxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aBohaker, Heidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Jennifer S.H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrownlee, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoutts, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevine, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleach, Frederic W., econtributor.4ctb4https: